Learn Network Scanning & Enumeration with Nmap
ğŸ“Œ Overview

Network scanning and enumeration are foundational skills in cybersecurity. Using Nmap (Network Mapper), you can discover hosts, identify open ports, detect services, and gather detailed information about systems on a network.

Nmap is widely used by:

Penetration testers

Security analysts

Network administrators

SOC teams

Learning Nmap helps you understand how attackers think â€” and how defenders detect and prevent attacks.

ğŸ§  What Is Network Scanning?

Network scanning is the process of identifying:

ğŸ”¹ Live hosts on a network

ğŸ”¹ Open ports

ğŸ”¹ Running services

ğŸ”¹ Operating systems

ğŸ”¹ Vulnerabilities

Enumeration goes deeper â€” extracting detailed information like:

User accounts

Service versions

SMB shares

DNS records

SNMP data

ğŸ›  Installing Nmap
Windows

Download from the official Nmap website.

Linux (Ubuntu/Debian)
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nmap
macOS (Homebrew)
brew install nmap

Verify installation:

nmap --version
ğŸš€ Phase 1: Basic Host Discovery
ğŸ”¹ Ping Scan (Discover Live Hosts)
nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24

-sn = No port scan

Finds which devices are online

Use this in your home lab network.

ğŸšª Phase 2: Port Scanning
ğŸ”¹ Scan a Single Target
nmap 192.168.1.10

Default scans top 1000 ports.

ğŸ”¹ Scan Specific Ports
nmap -p 22,80,443 192.168.1.10
ğŸ”¹ Scan All Ports
nmap -p- 192.168.1.10
ğŸ”¬ Phase 3: Service & Version Detection
nmap -sV 192.168.1.10

-sV = Detect service versions

Example output:

OpenSSH 8.2

Apache 2.4.41

This helps identify vulnerable versions.

ğŸ–¥ Phase 4: OS Detection
sudo nmap -O 192.168.1.10

-O = Operating system detection

Requires root/admin privileges

ğŸ”¥ Phase 5: Aggressive Scan (Common in Labs)
sudo nmap -A 192.168.1.10

Includes:

OS detection

Version detection

Script scanning

Traceroute

âš ï¸ Use only in authorized lab environments.

ğŸ“œ Phase 6: Enumeration with NSE (Nmap Scripting Engine)

Nmap includes powerful scripts for deeper enumeration.

ğŸ”¹ SMB Enumeration
nmap --script smb-enum-shares -p 445 192.168.1.10
ğŸ”¹ FTP Anonymous Login Check
nmap --script ftp-anon -p 21 192.168.1.10
ğŸ”¹ HTTP Enumeration
nmap --script http-enum -p 80 192.168.1.10
ğŸ”¹ Vulnerability Scan
nmap --script vuln 192.168.1.10
ğŸ§ª Practice Targets (Safe for Labs)

Use intentionally vulnerable systems like:

Metasploitable 2

OWASP Juice Shop

DVWA (Damn Vulnerable Web App)

Run them inside VirtualBox or VMware in an isolated network.

ğŸ“Š Sample Output Interpretation

Example:

PORT     STATE SERVICE VERSION
22/tcp   open  ssh     OpenSSH 7.6
80/tcp   open  http    Apache httpd 2.4.29
445/tcp  open  smb     Samba 3.6.25

What this tells you:

SSH is running

Web server present

SMB likely exploitable (older Samba version)

ğŸ›¡ Defensive Perspective

Learning Nmap helps defenders:

Detect exposed services

Identify misconfigurations

Audit firewall rules

Harden systems

Blue teams often use Nmap for internal audits.

ğŸ“š Learning Roadmap
